Scope

This document is to check the quality of the mapping performed with CellRanger tool from 10x Genomics. Specifically, visualization of the common mapping metrics obtained per library (sample) are considered.

Primary data

A total of two samples (Bone Marrow) were library-prepared and sequenced by CRG Sequencing platform at PRBB. Libraries were prepared using 10x Single Cell 3âv3 kit. Corresponding biological samples were delivered to the sequencing platform in Decemberâ24 and sequencing data was received in Februaryâ24. Each sample corresponds to a different condition:

  • CD45+ cells at 4.5 months (CD45_4_5)
  • CD45+ cells transplanted from KDR+ progenitors at 4.5 months (CD45_BFP_4_5) activated from 7* specific genes identified by CRISPRa in an earlier project phase.

Methods

Visualized results in this report have been generated by CellRanger v7.2.0 (Zheng et al. 2017) in a HPC environment using Singularity v3.8.3. Specifically, cellranger count was executed per sample to generate the corresponding data matrices. Introns were included in expression quantification as recommended by 10x Genomics (See for additional information https://www.10xgenomics.com/support/software/cell-ranger/latest/miscellaneous/cr-intron-mode-rec). Samples were aligned to ârefdata-gex-mm10-2020-Aâ transcriptome provided as well by 10x Genomics.

Results

Barcode Rank Plot

All three samples were successfully mapped to reference. Following figure shows the Barcode rank plot per sample. This plot shows the distribution of UMI counts in barcodes plotted in decreasing order of their corresponding number of UMIs. All samples show a typical (and good) behaviour with a âcliff and kneeâ shape. This is indicative of good separation between cell-associated barcodes and barcodes with empty emulsions. For more information on this, check: https://cdn.10xgenomics.com/image/upload/v1660261286/support-documents/CG000329_TechnicalNote_InterpretingCellRangerWebSummaryFiles_RevA.pdf

Overall statistics

Following metrics, per sample, are visualized:

  • general values: estimated number of cells, mean reads per cell and median genes per cell.
  • related to mapping quality: reads confidently (uniquely) map to intergenic/intronic or exonic regions.
  • sequencing saturation

General values: cells, reads and genes

The estimated number of cells per sample is:

The number of cells for each sample is:

  • CD45_4_5: 8461 cells.
  • CD45_BFP_4_5: 5635 cells.

Thus, the estimated number of cells is higher in the non transplanted cells.

The median genes per cell per sample is:

The median number of genes per cell for each sample is:

  • CD45_4_5: 1405 genes.
  • CD45_BFP_4_5: 1714 genes.

Thus, the median number of genes is higher in the transplanted cells.

The mean reads per cell per sample is:

The mean reads per cell for each sample is:

  • CD45_4_5: 24338 reads.
  • CD45_BFP_4_5: 34029 reads.

The mean reads per cell is uneven among samples, inversely proportional to the number of recovered cells.

Mapping quality: Reads confidently map to intergenic, intronic or exonic regions

In this section, percentage of reads mapped to intergenic, intronic or exonic regions of the reference are shown. Reads mapping to intergenic regions may be associated to contamination of ambient RNA. In this analysis, this potential contamination is not quantified but, in general terms, a 5% of contamination rate is usual. Mapping to intronic regions may be associated to unspliced RNA or mature RNA with retained introns.

Previous graphs show good mapping metrics for all samples, in fact, both of them behave quite similarly. Mapped reads to intergenic regions is contained (between 5-6%) and to genome is high (>86%). âIn general, for mouse we would expect >85% mapped reads to genome for a good experiment.â Percentage of reads mapping to intronic regions is <25% in both samples. This percentage is variable and depends on the tissue.

Sequencing saturation

Sequencing saturation is a measure of the fraction of library complexity that was captured during sequencing.
